<item>
            <title>[DAEMON-170] procrun passes garbage &quot;vfprintf&quot; passed to JVM options</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DAEMON-170</link>
                <project id="12310468" key="DAEMON">Commons Daemon</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;When starting a service, the list of passed JVM options seems to contain a garbage string after the generated classpath option and before the --JvmMx options:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;2010-08-05 16:24:21&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;debug&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; ( javajni.c:592 ) Jvm Option&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;38&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; -Dfoo=bar&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;2010-08-05 16:24:21&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;debug&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; ( javajni.c:592 ) Jvm Option&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;39&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; -Djava.class.path=D:\test.jar;d:\test2.jar;D:\test&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;2010-08-05 16:24:21&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;debug&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; ( javajni.c:592 ) Jvm Option&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;40&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; vfprintf &amp;lt;&amp;lt;---&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;2010-08-05 16:24:21&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;debug&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; ( javajni.c:592 ) Jvm Option&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;41&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; -Xms512m&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;2010-08-05 16:24:21&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;debug&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; ( javajni.c:592 ) Jvm Option&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;42&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; -Xmx1024m&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>&lt;p&gt;Windows XP SP3 32bit&lt;/p&gt;</environment>
        <key id="12470925">DAEMON-170</key>
            <summary>procrun passes garbage &quot;vfprintf&quot; passed to JVM options</summary>
                <type id="1" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/viewavatar?size=xsmall&amp;avatarId=21133&amp;avatarType=issuetype">Bug</type>
                                            <priority id="4" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/priorities/minor.svg">Minor</priority>
                        <status id="6" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/statuses/closed.png" description="The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are not closed can be reopened.">Closed</status>
                    <statusCategory id="3" key="done" colorName="green"/>
                                    <resolution id="6">Invalid</resolution>
                                        <assignee username="mturk@apache.org">Mladen Turk</assignee>
                                    <reporter username="b.eckenfels">Bernd Eckenfels</reporter>
                        <labels>
                    </labels>
                <created>Thu, 5 Aug 2010 17:09:09 +0000</created>
                <updated>Fri, 6 Aug 2010 06:05:18 +0000</updated>
                            <resolved>Fri, 6 Aug 2010 06:05:18 +0000</resolved>
                                    <version>1.0.3</version>
                                                    <component>Procrun</component>
                        <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>0</watches>
                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12895963" author="mturk@apache.org" created="Fri, 6 Aug 2010 06:05:18 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;vprintf is not an garbage.&lt;br/&gt;
It is used if you specify the -verbose:jni and it tells to JVM to use daemon&lt;br/&gt;
printf function for error messages.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is on by default and you can disable it using&lt;br/&gt;
--LogJniMessages=0&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
