<item>
            <title>[DAEMON-50] parameter check incorrect</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DAEMON-50</link>
                <project id="12310468" key="DAEMON">Commons Daemon</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The parameter check to require the &apos;=&apos; for the -D switch is incorrect.  Most of&lt;br/&gt;
the name=value parameters require this but a few such as&lt;br/&gt;
&apos;-Djava.security.manager&apos; does not.  With the inclusion of this check using this&lt;br/&gt;
option is impossible.  Also, the &apos;-version&apos; option isn&apos;t working.  I can use&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;del&gt;help/&lt;/del&gt;? and all of the other options, but &apos;-version&apos; returns the following:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;user@machine bin&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;$ ./jsvc -version&lt;br/&gt;
jsvc error: No class specified&lt;br/&gt;
jsvc error: Cannot parse command line arguments&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>&lt;p&gt;Operating System: Linux&lt;br/&gt;
Platform: PC&lt;/p&gt;</environment>
        <key id="12341210">DAEMON-50</key>
            <summary>parameter check incorrect</summary>
                <type id="1" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/viewavatar?size=xsmall&amp;avatarId=21133&amp;avatarType=issuetype">Bug</type>
                                            <priority id="3" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/priorities/major.svg">Major</priority>
                        <status id="6" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/statuses/closed.png" description="The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are not closed can be reopened.">Closed</status>
                    <statusCategory id="3" key="done" colorName="green"/>
                                    <resolution id="1">Fixed</resolution>
                                        <assignee username="-1">Unassigned</assignee>
                                    <reporter username="brian.whitehead@digitalevergreen.com">Brian Whitehead</reporter>
                        <labels>
                    </labels>
                <created>Sat, 17 Jan 2004 02:32:22 +0000</created>
                <updated>Tue, 14 Nov 2017 15:05:42 +0000</updated>
                            <resolved>Tue, 14 Nov 2017 15:05:42 +0000</resolved>
                                    <version>1.0 Alpha</version>
                                    <fixVersion>1.0.2</fixVersion>
                                        <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>0</watches>
                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12405828" author="william.barker@wilshire.com" created="Mon, 19 Jan 2004 10:36:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The &apos;-D&apos; problem is fixed now in the CVS, and will appear in the next release.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If &apos;-debug&apos; is specified, then jsvc will warn about -D options that don&apos;t &lt;br/&gt;
contain an &apos;=&apos;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t agree that &apos;./jsvc -version&apos; should work (since it should just return &lt;br/&gt;
the same thing as &apos;java -version&apos;).  The option is intended to help you to &lt;br/&gt;
debug broken scripts.  Since the output of &apos;./jsvc -version&apos; would get sent &lt;br/&gt;
to /dev/null, it doesn&apos;t seem to be that useful to support.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
