<item>
            <title>[DAEMON-43] [daemon] stdout not working when installed as windows service</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DAEMON-43</link>
                <project id="12310468" key="DAEMON">Commons Daemon</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;When starting a tomcat service installed with tomcat.exe, the stdout/stderr &lt;br/&gt;
log files are not getting written.  The files are created, but their size &lt;br/&gt;
remains at zero.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tomcat &lt;b&gt;is&lt;/b&gt; producing output - when I run it from a console window, it spews &lt;br/&gt;
all kinds of stuff.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is the command line I use to install it as a service:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;tomcat.exe //IS//Tomcat \&lt;br/&gt;
  --Java c:\install\3rdparty\java1.4.2-win\bin\server\jvm.dll \&lt;br/&gt;
  -&lt;del&gt;JavaOptions -Dcotagesoft.home=c:/install#&lt;/del&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
Djava.endorsed.dirs=c:/install/3rdparty/jakarta-tomcat-5.0.18/common/endorsed#-&lt;br/&gt;
Djava.class.path=c:/install/3rdparty/java1.4.2-&lt;br/&gt;
win/lib/tools.jar;c:/install/3rdparty/jakarta-tomcat-5.0.18/bin/bootstrap.jar#-&lt;br/&gt;
Dcatalina.base=c:/install/3rdparty/jakarta-tomcat-5.0.18#-&lt;br/&gt;
Dcatalina.home=c:/cotagesoft/3rdparty/jakarta-tomcat-5.0.18#-&lt;br/&gt;
Djava.io.tmpdir=c:/install/3rdparty/jakarta-tomcat-5.0.18/tmp \&lt;br/&gt;
  --ImagePath c:/install/3rdparty/jakarta-tomcat-5.0.18/bin/bootstrap.jar \&lt;br/&gt;
  --StartupClass org.apache.catalina.startup.Bootstrap;main;start \&lt;br/&gt;
  --ShutdownClass org.apache.catalina.startup.Bootstrap;main;stop \&lt;br/&gt;
  --StdOutputFile c:\install\logs\stdout.log \&lt;br/&gt;
  --StdErrorFile c:\install\logs\stderr.log \&lt;br/&gt;
  --WorkingPath c:/install&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>&lt;p&gt;Operating System: All&lt;br/&gt;
Platform: Other&lt;/p&gt;</environment>
        <key id="12341254">DAEMON-43</key>
            <summary>[daemon] stdout not working when installed as windows service</summary>
                <type id="1" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/viewavatar?size=xsmall&amp;avatarId=21133&amp;avatarType=issuetype">Bug</type>
                                            <priority id="3" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/priorities/major.svg">Major</priority>
                        <status id="6" iconUrl="https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/statuses/closed.png" description="The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are not closed can be reopened.">Closed</status>
                    <statusCategory id="3" key="done" colorName="green"/>
                                    <resolution id="1">Fixed</resolution>
                                        <assignee username="-1">Unassigned</assignee>
                                    <reporter username="herold@cotagesoft.com">Robert Herold</reporter>
                        <labels>
                    </labels>
                <created>Tue, 10 Feb 2004 06:39:24 +0000</created>
                <updated>Tue, 14 Nov 2017 15:05:51 +0000</updated>
                            <resolved>Tue, 14 Nov 2017 15:05:51 +0000</resolved>
                                    <version>1.0 Alpha</version>
                                    <fixVersion>1.0.2</fixVersion>
                                        <due></due>
                            <votes>1</votes>
                                    <watches>0</watches>
                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12405961" author="remm@apache.org" created="Tue, 10 Feb 2004 22:33:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This works for me if the service is installed correctly (as done using the&lt;br/&gt;
installer), either in &quot;console&quot; mode or as a service. Please do not reopen this&lt;br/&gt;
report.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12405962" author="herold@cotagesoft.com" created="Wed, 11 Feb 2004 02:53:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;True, it does work when using the Windows installer.  That&apos;s the whole point - &lt;br/&gt;
it doesn&apos;t work when using the command line tool to install the service.  I &lt;br/&gt;
need to script the installation, so I can&apos;t use the GUI installer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It would be helpful to have a step-by-step HOWTO on using the command line &lt;br/&gt;
tomcat.exe to install the service - perhaps I am just using it incorrectly.  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since you say not to reopen the bug, I&apos;ll just revert to using the tomcat 4.1 &lt;br/&gt;
command line service installer (bin/tomcat.exe).  That one worked like a charm.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12405963" author="remm@apache.org" created="Wed, 11 Feb 2004 03:09:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Use bin\service.bat instead.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12405964" author="william.barker@wilshire.com" created="Wed, 11 Feb 2004 03:55:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Actually, this is what happens when you use --Java c:\path\to\jvm.dll.  You &lt;br/&gt;
only get the output redirection with --Java java.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12405965" author="herold@cotagesoft.com" created="Wed, 11 Feb 2004 05:27:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I verified that if you use tomcat&apos;s service.bat, and change &quot;-&lt;del&gt;Java java&quot; to &quot;&lt;/del&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
-Java path\to\jvm.dll, then the stdout file gets created but never written.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is this the intended behavior, or a bug?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is there any workaround, other than installing java normally?  I want to use &lt;br/&gt;
this on systems onto which I simply copy the java distribution w/o running the &lt;br/&gt;
java installer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(Apologies if this is not the appropriate forum for asking this kind of stuff).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12405966" author="william.barker@wilshire.com" created="Wed, 11 Feb 2004 15:16:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yeah, it&apos;s a bug.  It will take a little work to fix, so it is possible that I &lt;br/&gt;
might hold off until the next commons-deamon release is out the door.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And Remy, this bug is now properly assigned to commons-deamon, so please don&apos;t &lt;br/&gt;
close it again, since I will simply reopen &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12405967" author="william.barker@wilshire.com" created="Fri, 2 Apr 2004 03:24:06 +0000"  >&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;*** Bug 28138 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. *** has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="12405968" author="mturk@apache.org" created="Sun, 17 Apr 2005 18:16:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This has been fixed in more recent builds.&lt;br/&gt;
The problem is that we don&apos;t have a separate binary distribution for&lt;br/&gt;
procrun.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12557605" author="dennisl@apache.org" created="Thu, 10 Jan 2008 11:57:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Setting resolution&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
